I love rituals and routines, and since summer, yoga is a part of my night time routine. I don't always practice for long, sometimes just 15 min, but I do it everyday, even when I'm sick or on my period. I always feel better afterwards because I feel like I've done something good for myself. The hardest part was to start, and stop making excuses for not doing it. I thought I hadn't the time but that wasn't true. Practices don't have to last an hour, they can be 15 min. Most of us can do it, most people can find15 min of free time everyday, if we're willing to get off our phones. That's how I started, I just reduced my social media/news time in the evening (I still check them during the day, but very rarely at night). I started with short practices and after a while, I found myself craving more. These days, I do about 40-50 minutes every night, except when I'm really tired. Now that it's a part of my routine, and I don't even think of not doing it. I just go home from work at 9 p.m, eat a little snack, roll off my mat, do my yoga, shower and then it's relaxation time :)
Have a great week end Adriene and all of you, see you tomorrow :)

Deep into winter here in western Massachusetts, my ritual is to go for exploratory hikes in the snow and track animals. I happily lose myself and I piece together clues. I try to reenact the info I gather from the tracks. Oh look, this coyote stopped on top of this rock. I wonder what he/she was thinking/smelling/feeling...this fox started running here. I wonder why? This deer started digging for something here. I wonder where she sleeps? I find it to be beautifully meditative. The clean, crisp winter forest air feels great to breathe in. I feel like I connect with our non-human animal friends, our ancestors, and I have a deep appreciation for the Indigenous people (Mohicans) of our lands.

Adriene: Let everything go
Me: But there's so much I'm holding on to, how do I let it all go?
Adriene (or my conscience inspired by all my Yoga practices with Adriene): Why are you holding onto it?
Me: So I can fix it... if I keep it present with me I can work on fixing it?
Adriene: How does holding onto all the burdens help you fix them?
Me: It doesn't. It weighs me down
Adriene: Maybe letting go of all your burdens is how you fix things in your life? Maybe focusing on each moment, with love, will help bring the healing you and your family need?

Later
Me: This Pandemic has been so difficult for so many people  in so many different ways... I want to remember to Love even if I do not feel loved. 
I'm the one thing I can control in my life. I'd rather explore filling it with love... rather than make sure everyone shows love how I think they should show love to others.
That doesn't mean I don't have boundaries I lovingly stick to... but it does mean that I try to Breath Love in and Breath Love Out... Feel love in my heart even when I don't agree (even vehemently so)... I can still work on filling my heart with love...

We are huge fans of using rituals for our yoga and meditation practices. For us it's preparing some tea, listening to some calming music and setting up our dedicated space to practice. We actually recently did a music video called ritual and researched their importance. Not only do rituals give you the opportunity to create habits but they are also unique in their ability to ground you in a specific moment. Because rituals are for all intents and purposes, habits, they become learned behaviours and our brains begin to expect them. We get a sense of satisfaction upon completing it and this is due to a release of dopamine in our brains. Therefore, our brains, which are pre-disposed to order exist in expectation of the completion of certain habitual actions, and we get a boost of dopamine when this need is fulfilled.
